      <hedline>
        <hl1>Shot-Putter Says Threat Effective</hl1>
      </hedline>
      <byline class="print_byline">AP</byline>
      <dateline>TORONTO, April 26</dateline>
    </body.head>
    <body.content>
      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>LEAD: A shot-putter suspended for using banned drugs said today that he was reinstated by the Canadian Track and Field Association after he threatened to expose steroid use by the sprinter Ben Johnson and his teammates.</p>
      </block>
      <block class="full_text">
        <p>LEAD: A shot-putter suspended for using banned drugs said today that he was reinstated by the Canadian Track and Field Association after he threatened to expose steroid use by the sprinter Ben Johnson and his teammates.</p>
        <p>A shot-putter suspended for using banned drugs said today that he was reinstated by the Canadian Track and Field Association after he threatened to expose steroid use by the sprinter Ben Johnson and his teammates.</p>
        <p>Peter Dajia told a Canadian inquiry that the track group acted quickly once it was told its biggest star was using a banned substance.</p>
        <p>Dajia said his appeals were rejected and his 18-month suspension lingered for two years. He then threatened to expose Johnson. Several days later, the association began proceedings to reinstate Dajia.</p>
      </block>
